ve guarded, although there is no such things as secrets in Eden Park School.<br /></p> <p>This book was such an enlightening read and I was captivated. David and Leo`s story is just special and all the struggles they go through are realistic, making the book even more interesting. Even though transgender issues are a controversial topic, Williamson writes so that this genre doesn’t take over the whole book but it is still the main subject; she does this by adding some growing-up themes and a teenage voice. This makes the book much easier to read and you can relate to the characters.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445/0_0_257_400/257.jpg\" alt=\"fdf\" width=\"257\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Furthermore the plot twist that happens half-way through the book was completely unexpected. The plot twist was necessary because the book was dragging a bit and there wasn’t any “action” so you needed something to keep the interest of the reader; the plot twist did this. I enjoyed the plot twist because it made me realise that sometimes life isn’t fair and you always need to follow you heart. The characters were just so real and some people could say they were inspirational because they have always stuck to their gut instincts.</p> <p>Overall I enjoyed this book and I found it an easy read that consisted of LGBTQ+ themes and coming-of-age themes. I recommend this book to everyone because I think that everyone will benefit from this book and read about a story that we have not heard as much. It was also an enjoyable read which you won’t have any trouble reading.  </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <ul> <li><strong>Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/360861/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></li> </ul> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read?<a href=\"http://preview.gutools.co.uk/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fbct","wordcount":"330","standfirst":"<p>‘The characters were just so real and inspirational because they always stuck to their gut instincts’</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/the-art-of-being-normal-lisa-williamson-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/the-art-of-being-normal-lisa-williamson-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445/0_0_257_400/257.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445","altText":"fdf","caption":"","source":"Guardian Bookshop","credit":"Photograph: Guardian Bookshop","mediaId":"bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445/0_0_257_400/257.jpg","width":"257","height":"400"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445/0_0_257_400/master/257.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445","altText":"fdf","caption":"","source":"Guardian Bookshop","credit":"Photograph: Guardian Bookshop","mediaId":"bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445/0_0_257_400/master/257.jpg","width":"257","height":"400","isMaster":"true"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]},{"id":"_no_ids","relation":"body","type":"embed","assets":[{"type":"embed","file":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books","typeData":{"embedType":"rich-link","linkText":"How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?","linkPrefix":"Related: "}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Children's books","type":"blog","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-books","webTitle":"Teen books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/friendship","webTitle":"Friendship (children and teens)","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/friendship","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/friendship","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/school","webTitle":"School","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/school","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/school","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-romance","webTitle":"Teen romance (childrens and teens)","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-romance","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-romance","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/childrens-user-reviews","webTitle":"Children's user reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-08T12:00:13Z","webTitle":"The best recent thrillers – reviews roundup","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"books/2016/jan/08/best-recent-thrillers-reviews-roundup","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"John O'Connell","headline":"The best recent thrillers – reviews roundup","trailText":"<strong>John O’Connell:</strong> Coffin Road by Peter May; Rain Dogs by Adrian McKinty; The Widow by Fiona Barton; Black Widow by Chris Brookmyre; Viral by Helen Fitzgerald","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"e86adaecd66feca2756e903a9493bdd16001050e\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e86adaecd66feca2756e903a9493bdd16001050e/0_0_260_400/260.jpg\" alt=\"peter may\" width=\"260\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>Veteran thriller writer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jan/26/peter-may-returning-to-a-runaway-youth\">Peter May</a> is on a roll after the huge success of the <a href=\"http://www.ur-web.net/PeterMayMain/lewispage.html\">Lewis Trilogy</a> and <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/entry-island.html\">Entry Island</a>. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/359390/\"><strong>Coffin Road</strong></a> (Quercus, £18.99) returns us to the Outer Hebrides, in this case Harris, where in the opening chapter a man is washed up on the shore, unable to remember who or what he is. It transpires that he is, or may be, a writer who has been researching the mysterious disappearance of the keepers from the Flannan Isles lighthouse in December 1900. But when he returns to the lighthouse to corroborate his theory, he finds a dead body in a nearby chapel. Which raises the question: is he also a murderer? From this bare premise May conjures a clever, twisty eco-thriller in the mode of Le Carré’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/constant-gardener.html\"><em>The Constant Gardener</em></a>. Selective amnesia is hard to render convincingly – your sense as a reader is usually that it has more to do with plotting convenience than neurology – but May just about pulls it off, while making the atmospheric most of his isolated locations.<br /></p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"32fe7a9768c61fd64a6cfc24ae31075537060099\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/32fe7a9768c61fd64a6cfc24ae31075537060099/0_0_262_400/262.jpg\" alt=\"Book jacket of Rain Dogs by Adrian McKinty\" width=\"262\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/adrian-mckinty\">Adrian McKinty</a>’s Sean Duffy thrillers set in 1980s Belfast come thick and fast, but the quality remains constant. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/362982/\"><strong>Rain Dogs</strong></a> (Serpent’s Tail, £12.99) finds the sarcastic detective investigating the apparent suicide of a Financial Times journalist at Carrickfergus castle. It turns out to be a murder, and the second locked-room mystery of Duffy’s police career. The tension between McKinty’s competing love of tight, formal puzzles and loose, riffing dialogue is what makes the Duffy novels such a joy. McGinty indulges himself here, inventing a visit to Belfast by Muhammad Ali and packing Duffy and his colleagues off to Broadmoor to interview Jimmy Savile in his creepy caravan. The latter scene feels a bit <em>avant la lettre</em>, but is enormous fun. (“He’s a bit different with the cameras off, isn’t he?” Lawson said. “He’s a bit of a … ” “Fuckface?” I suggested.) The last chapters suggest Duffy may be on the verge of becoming a responsible adult. I hope not.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"bc44c73f7254f37b31cfff7b245ed5bb6d468ba7\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/bc44c73f7254f37b31cfff7b245ed5bb6d468ba7/0_0_260_400/260.jpg\" alt=\"Book jacket of The Widow by Fiona Barton\" width=\"260\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>As a journalist for the Daily Mail, <a href=\"http://fionabartonauthor.com/\">Fiona Barton</a> reported on some notorious court cases. Her much‑hyped debut <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/361124/\"><strong>The Widow</strong></a> (Bantam, £12.99) is marinated in awful knowledge gleaned in the course of her work and as a result feels solid and convincing. Essentially it is the story of Jean Taylor, whose husband Glen was accused of abducting a two-year-old girl. Now that Glen is dead, Jean is free to tell her story to journalist Kate Waters, who is poised to whisk her away to a luxury hotel where the grand inquisition will take place. But what is that story, exactly? How much did Jean know about the paedophile activities she calls “his nonsense”? Barton is fascinated by the way loyalty breeds both denial and collusion, and has channelled that into a taut, highly effective thriller. My one reservation is Jean’s odd voice, which feels too 1950s-prim – an upper-middle-class person’s slightly dated idea of how lower-middle-class people speak. But then, Glen and Jean are nothing if not strange, so perhaps that extends to their domestic idiolect.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"df2003fd13423f626e0d4432517f321fe7171a30\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/df2003fd13423f626e0d4432517f321fe7171a30/0_0_261_400/261.jpg\" alt=\"Book jacket of Black Widow by Chris Brookmyre\" width=\"261\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>Publishing’s obsession with shiny debuts rightly annoys veteran novelists who understand that practise makes perfect. It is 20 years since <a href=\"http://www.brookmyre.co.uk/\">Chris Brookmyre</a>’s debut <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/quite-ugly-one-morning-2.html\"><em>Quite Ugly One Morning</em></a>, but <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/360443/\"><strong>Black Widow</strong></a> (Little, Brown, £18.99), his latest thriller featuring journalist Jack Parlabane, is exceptionally good – a knotty mystery that’s not just richly, provocatively political but one of the most perceptive excavations of a dysfunctional marriage I can remember reading. The unhappy couple are driven surgeon Diana Jager and IT guy Peter, who seems to be the tonic she needs. Diana’s life has been a mess since she was revealed to be the anonymous author of a blog exposing sexism in surgery. But then Peter is killed in a car accident … Brookmyre plays a cunning, careful game, allowing Diana to co-narrate so plausibly that we are never sure if she is genuinely empathetic (and therefore unfairly maligned as a psychopath) or just brilliant at emulating emotion for our benefit.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"e659a23e995750f2c4973571b45734bd7702f531\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e659a23e995750f2c4973571b45734bd7702f531/0_0_260_400/260.jpg\" alt=\"Book jacket of Viral by Helen Fitzgerald\" width=\"260\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>The embarrassing video that goes viral leaving misery in its wake is fast becoming a thriller cliche. Helen Fitzgerald’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/370109/\"><strong>Viral</strong></a> (Faber, £12.99) has a look-at-me opening sentence – “I sucked 12 cocks in Magaluf” – that doesn’t bode well, but quickly redeems itself, developing into a nuanced and perceptive look at social media and misogyny. At its heart is the old-fashioned, analogue story of shallow, bullying Leah and her clever adopted sister Su, who goes to earth when an uncharacteristic lapse of judgment wrecks her life. Their furious mother, who is a judge, packs Leah off to Spain to look for Su while she plans her revenge on the man who first uploaded the clip. A good one for older teens.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fbbc","wordcount":"808","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/59cd1a930bffb2641953345b61eee04d4cf7f560/0_101_4368_2621/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-02-19T14:48:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Coffin Road by Peter May; Rain Dogs by Adrian McKinty; The Widow by Fiona Barton; Black Widow by Chris Brookmyre; Viral by Helen Fitzgerald</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/08/best-recent-thrillers-reviews-roundup","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/jan/08/best-recent-thrillers-reviews-roundup","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"59cd1a930bffb2641953345b61eee04d4cf7f560","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/59cd1a930bffb2641953345b61eee04d4cf7f560/0_0_4368_2912/2000.jpg","typeDat