Law","references":[]},{"id":"world/unitednations","webTitle":"United Nations","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/unitednations","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/unitednations","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"world/world","webTitle":"World news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/world","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/world","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]},{"id":"profile/alisonflood","webTitle":"Alison Flood","r2ContributorId":"27440","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/3/14/1300117336779/Alison.jpg","firstName":"","lastName":"flood","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Alison Flood is a writer on guardian.co.uk/books and former news editor of the Bookseller</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alisonflood","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/alisonflood","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-08T11:00:10Z","webTitle":"Poster poems: clay","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/jan/08/poster-poems-clay","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Billy Mills","headline":"Poster poems: clay","trailText":"That from which the first man was made, or the ground in which nothing grows … clay has associations with both creation and decay. Send us your poems about the sticky stuff, either way","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>When you hear the word “soil”, you tend to think of growth, organic life, fertility. “Clay” is another matter entirely. It’s dead, sticky and wet, it sucks you down, nothing grows in it, it’s useful only to the potter. While this may be a little unfair to the stuff, I suspect that this is how most of us view it.</p> <p>But there is another side to clay. In the Bible creation story, as in many other similar myths, God made the first man from clay, and this association of clay and flesh endures in modern literature.</p> <p>In Patrick Kavanagh’s long poem <a href=\"http://allpoetry.com/The-Great-Hunger\">The Great Hunger</a>, clay takes on the character of a malevolent deity from the opening line: “Clay is the word and clay is the flesh.” The echo of the Gospel of St John reflects the idea that the heavy Monaghan earth from which Maguire, the protagonist of the poem, wrestles a living is both his god and the locus of his slow, frustrated death-in-life. The end of the poem is an “apocalypse of clay”; a vision of abandoned hopelessness, with Maguire a lustless, lifeless clay figure of a man.</p> <p>For Frederick Manning, <a href=\"http://www.bartleby.com/266/93.html\">writing from the front</a> during the first world war, the trenches were “Endless lanes sunken in the clay”, ironically vivid with wild flowers, but also somewhat like arteries and veins running through the clay of the soldiers’ bodies. And in the background, the choice of clay rather than earth or mud reminds the reader that these trenches would end up serving as graves for many of these same bodies.</p> <p>A world war later, the child <a href=\"http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poem/245046\">Roy Fisher</a> sees the bombed garden where his aunt, his two cousins and their neighbour died as “a pod filled with clay”, with the centre of the crater a “smooth clay saucer”. The twin meanings of the word, literal and metaphorical, fold into one another in images of quiet power.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"b84a646a417b042f13f4148e0c764f9f4276617e\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/b84a646a417b042f13f4148e0c764f9f4276617e/0_665_7216_4330/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Two Cows by Stephanie Quayle (2013), clay, chicken wire, steel.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Two Cows by Stephanie Quayle (2013). Clay, chicken wire, steel.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Stephanie Quayle/Saatchi Gallery</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>This association of clay and death is as old as poetry. In <a href=\"http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.03.0064%3Asonnet%3DLXXI\">Sonnet LXXII</a>, Shakespeare uses the rhyme with “decay” to emphasise the finality of the separation of lovers that happens when one of them dies. In his poem <a href=\"http://www.scottishpoetrylibrary.org.uk/poetry/poems/nigg\">Nigg</a>, the Scottish poet Ken Morrice reminds us that clay is part of a geological reality that is far older than poetry, and links red sandstone, red clay and the blood of the dead who lie buried in it in a single process of natural indifference.</p> <p>Of course, for many poets the reality of clay is as interesting as its symbolic meanings. <a href=\"http://www.bartleby.com/165/18.html\">Carl Sandburg</a>, characteristically, saw it as a source of work – hard, back-breaking, boot-sucking labour, to be pitied or envied depending on the onlooker.</p> <p>Of all the poets who have written about clay, the one who was most fully immersed in it was Jack Clemo, whose centenary falls later this year. Clemo lived and died in the clay country of Cornwall, an area that supplied the potteries of Britain with much of their raw material, and his poetry is saturated with the stuff. Clemo was deaf and blind for most of his writing life, which might help explain the attraction of this tactile material to him as a poet. Also, his deeply held religious beliefs and his ecological views infused his view of clay as more than mere matter.</p> <p>In poems such as <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.sense-of-place.co.uk/Rescorla/clemo.htm\">The Clay Pit Worker</a>, Clemo celebrated nature’s power of survival, the resilience of life which means that even the most unpromisingly clayey bit of waste ground is ultimately reclaimed by the green world. You don’t have to share the specifically religious aspect of his vision to share his delight in this regeneration.</p> <p>And so this month, we turn our poetic attention to clay in all its malleable forms. You may think of clay as the word, the flesh or the pits, or any combination of these things. It’s time to dig into your inspiration pit and shape the material you find there into a well-wrought urn in verse.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fhgk","wordcount":"665","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/5aec19a8e07e4200d76a2ce2e9f06e129825bf6f/0_55_2000_1201/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-02-05T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>That from which the first man was made, or the ground in which nothing grows … clay has associations with both creation and decay. Send us your poems about the sticky stuff, either way</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/08/poster-poems-clay","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/jan/08/poster-poems-clay","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"5aec19a8e07e4200d76a2ce2e9f06e129825bf6f","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/5aec19a8e07e4200d76a2ce2e9f06e129825bf6f/0_55_2000_1201/140.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/5aec19a8e07e4200d76a2ce2e9f06e129825bf6f","suppliersReference":"AAP474","altText":"Feet of clay … a fossilised ancient human footprint in the clay of Mungo national park, Australia.","caption":"Feet of clay … a fossilised ancient human footprint in the clay of Mungo national park, Australia.","photographer":"Michael Amendolia","source":"AAP Image","credit":"Photograph: Michael Amendolia/AAP Image","mediaId":"5a