http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"tone/reviews","webTitle":"Reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/reviews","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/kate-clanchy","webTitle":"Kate Clanchy","r2ContributorId":"33797","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2009/8/20/1250780715827/kate.jpg","firstName":"kate","lastName":"clanchy","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Kate Clanchy is a poet, author and journalist. Her book Antigona and Me is published in paperback by Picador</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/kate-clanchy","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/kate-clanchy","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/guardianreview","webTitle":"Guardian review","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/guardianreview","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/guardianreview","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/guardianreview/saturdayreviewsfeatres","webTitle":"Features & reviews","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/guardianreview/saturdayreviewsfeatres","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/guardianreview/saturdayreviewsfeatres","sectionName":"Books","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-08T09:58:57Z","webTitle":"Robin Stevens: 'Plan your crime, the moment that it happened and who did it'","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/robin-stevens-murder-most-unladylike-jolly-foul-play","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"Mars Bar27","headline":"Robin Stevens: 'Plan your crime, the moment that it happened and who did it'","trailText":"Site member Mars Bar27 met Robin Stevens at the Books on Tyne festival and got inside info on the fourth Murder Most Unladylike book, Jolly Foul Play, which comes out in March","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>I was lucky enough to meet author Robin Stevens in Newcastle just before Christmas at the <a href=\"http://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/books-on-tyne-the-newcastle-book-festival-2015-tickets-17566346415\">Books on Tyne festival</a> at <a href=\"http://www.litandphil.org.uk/\">The Lit &amp; Phil</a>. There were so many great events. I saw Anne Fine, who told us how she started school at three years old and that that children often mistake her name for Anne Frank. Then I met David Almond and heard he had found his book <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/skellig-8.html\">Skellig</a> really easy to write. Robin Stevens’ event was all about murder mysteries. We discovered loads about her upcoming Murder Most Unladylike mystery book <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/380416/\">Jolly Foul Play</a> (the fourth in the series, out in March), which is going to be set back at Deepdean. I got to have a one-to-one chat with Robin after the event, so I hope you enjoy my interview. I can’t wait for the next Books on Tyne festival to meet more authors next year!</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"78c9116a27a429cfc30305f85a166d72b879d81a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/78c9116a27a429cfc30305f85a166d72b879d81a/0_0_1538_2339/658.jpg\" alt=\"First Class Murder cover\" width=\"658\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p><strong>Mars Bar27: Your books are set in the 1930s, do you think the Wells and Wong series will eventually reach the war?</strong><br /></p> <p>Robin: I’m trying to age them up slowly because I’d them like to stay as young teenagers. If they got a year older in each book like Harry Potter, they’d age too quickly. I’m definitely moving towards the war, as the fifth book will take place at the end of 1935. If they did reach the war, I know what they would do. Hazel would work at Bletchley Park as a code-breaker and Daisy would be a spy, like <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/charlotte-gray.html\">Charlotte Gray</a>. I have ideas for what they could do in the war, and it would be lovely to write up to that point or to write something set in the future.</p> <p><strong>Do you think if you have set it later in the 1930s, it would reach that point?</strong></p> <p>I definitely chose 1934 as the setting for my first book on purpose, because it’s written in between the first and second world wars, and nobody seems to know much about that time. I’m also a big fan of history!</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/aug/20/robin-stevenss-top-10-capers\">Robin Stevens's top 10 crime capers</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>I’ve heard one of your books may be turned into a TV series. Which of your books that you would most want to see on screen?</strong></p> <p>I’d love to have a series, and the producer wants to film each one of them for TV! The one I’d most like to see as a TV show is <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/arsenic-for-tea.html\">Arsenic for Tea</a> because I love the setting and there are such great characters.</p> <p><strong>If you could be in the TV series yourself, who would you play?</strong></p> <p>I’d play a tree or a maid - I’m not very good at acting. There was an author whose books were made into a TV show and she got to be in the background, so I think that’s what I would want.</p> <p><strong>What would be your ideal bun break treat?</strong></p> <p>If it was a cake, it would be coffee or walnut cake and if it was a biscuit, it would be a chocolate chip cookie or gingerbread.</p> <p><strong>In your books, you mention how Hazel hates the squashed fly biscuits – do you agree?</strong></p> <p>I hated them when I was Hazel’s age, there’s always the moment when you realise that it’s not chocolate.</p> <p><strong>Have you got any other ideas for the detective society?</strong></p> <p>Book five is a Christmas themed one, which will take place in Cambridge, because Daisy’s brother goes to Cambridge and they are visiting him for the holidays. It will be based in a college, in the snow, but I haven’t planned it out yet.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"9b8505146515bccf3a4e0410947cd045fa47902d\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9b8505146515bccf3a4e0410947cd045fa47902d/0_0_1524_2339/652.jpg\" alt=\"Jolly Foul Play cover\" width=\"652\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p><strong>In your new book (out 24 March) <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/380416/\">Jolly Foul Play</a>, the fourth book in the Murder Most Unladylike series, you said there will be some new characters - are some of the original students going to return?</strong></p> <p>Kitty and Beanie come back as bigger roles, and Lavinia, who didn’t play a huge role in the other books. This time she also joins the detective society, which is really cool. There are also younger girls who play bigger roles like Betsy North and Binnie (Kitty’s little sister). I couldn’t bring back many teachers, so it’s all new big girls, head girls and teachers. This time it’s one of the big girls who is the victim!</p> <p><strong>In your first book Murder Most Unladylike, you describe Lavinia as if she was angry, she’d just knock someone over.</strong></p> <p>Yes, she’s got so much rage! Someone asked me who I was most like apart from Hazel, and I said Lavinia. She’s me when I’m most angry - she’s so aggressive.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>And finally have you got any tips for aspiring crime writers?</strong></p> <p>Plan your crime, the moment that it happened and who did it, and why. Have those facts in your head. I’m not an author who does a detailed plan, but it’s important that you know the crime yourself so you have control. Also read lots of crime novels to get inspired.</p> <p><strong>Robin Steven’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/380416/\">Jolly Foul Play is out in March, but available to pre-order from the Guardian bookshop</a>. Want to interview your favour author? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the Guardian children’s books site and we might be able to arrange it! </a></strong></p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4enkh","wordcount":"882","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/d7e459ac81757b486cd99add57ef7d22758b83f4/0_62_2200_1320/140.jpg","standfirst":"<p>Site member Mars Bar27 met Robin Stevens at the Books on Tyne festival and got inside info on the fourth Murder Most Unladylike book, Jolly Foul Play, which comes out in March</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/robin-stevens-murder-most-unladylike-jolly-foul-play","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/robin-stevens-murder-most-unladylike-jolly-foul-play","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"d