w.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/childrens-books-8-12-years","webTitle":"Children's books: 8-12 years","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/series/childrens-books-author-q-as","webTitle":"Children's books: author Q&As","description":"Celebrated children's books authors discuss the inspirations behind some of their best-loved works","type":"series","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/childrens-books-author-q-as","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/series/childrens-books-author-q-as","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/crime","webTitle":"Crime fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/crime","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/crime","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/interview","webTitle":"Interviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/interview","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/interview","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-08T09:00:11Z","webTitle":"Sophie Someone by Hayley Long – review","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/sophie-someone-hayley-long-review","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"ThoughtfulReader","headline":"Sophie Someone by Hayley Long – review","trailText":"<strong>ThoughtfulReader: ‘</strong>I think this is a brilliant and unique novel with fascinating word choices and a captivating plot’","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>In this novel, the reader follows Sophie as she learns that her parents have kept many secrets from her and her brother Hercule. Sophie’s family live in Brussels, capital of Belgium. But Sophie’s family haven’t always lived there. Sophie has memories of coming on the train from England, and she wonders if she’s somehow fabricated the truth as she seems to remember odd things about the journey like her mother putting on a wig in the station toilets. But that can’t have really happened… can it? </p> <p>This book is unlike any other book I’ve ever read. I was completely taken by surprise at how cleverly some ordinary words were substituted for others throughout the whole novel. The story is narrated by Sophie, and for example, instead of using the word internet, she used the word introvert. In a sentence, you would immediately understand what Sophie meant without having to reread the sentence and it’s crazy how well this works. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4/0_0_245_400/245.jpg\" alt=\"fdf\" width=\"245\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Here’s a sentence I picked out from the book</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In the living root, I chucked myself down on the softy and lay – fax down – on the softy’s big squishy cushions.</p> </blockquote> <p>Here, it’s obvious that root means room, softy is a replacement for sofa, and by fax Sophie means face. This sentence can be read almost without realising that some words have been replaced. And once I was into the second chapter, I think I stopped noticing at all, it just seemed natural. But sometimes, I had to pause and try and think what word Sophie meant, and when this happened, it was quite frustrating to be honest, and the flow of the novel was lost. This was the only thing which I disliked. But on the whole, I think the replacing of words worked really well. It really makes the writing style unique and keeps the reader interested.</p> <p>Overall, I think this is a brilliant and unique novel with fascinating word choices and a captivating plot. I would recommend this to children aged thirteen and upwards because it is not always easy to understand what the ordinary word is which Sophie is replacing. I think this book is certainly is a good contender for the 2015 Costa Children’s Book Award prize.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <ul> <li><strong>Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/329280/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></li> </ul> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read?<a href=\"http://preview.gutools.co.uk/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fbbd","wordcount":"407","standfirst":"<p>‘I think this is a brilliant and unique novel with fascinating word choices and a captivating plot’</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/sophie-someone-hayley-long-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/sophie-someone-hayley-long-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4/0_0_245_400/245.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4","altText":"fdf","caption":"","source":"Guardian Bookshop","credit":"Photograph: Guardian Bookshop","mediaId":"fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4/0_0_245_400/245.jpg","width":"245","height":"400"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4/0_0_245_400/master/245.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4","altText":"fdf","caption":"","source":"Guardian Bookshop","credit":"Photograph: Guardian Bookshop","mediaId":"fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/fb47b93f96732898863097be594f327a3bb99cf4/0_0_245_400/master/245.jpg","width":"245","height":"400","isMaster":"true"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]},{"id":"_no_ids","relation":"body","type":"embed","assets":[{"type":"embed","file":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books","typeData":{"embedType":"rich-link","linkText":"How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?","linkPrefix":"Related: "}}]}],"tags":[{"id":"childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Children's books","type":"blog","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-books","webTitle":"Teen books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/friendship","webTitle":"Friendship (children and teens)","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/friendship","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/friendship","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/adventure","webTitle":"Adventure (children and teens)","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/adventure","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/adventure","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/childrens-user-reviews","webTitle":"Children's user reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-08T08:29:17Z","webTitle":"We need to talk about mental health without shame","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/teen-mental-health-ibs-juno-dawson","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"Juno Dawson","headline":"We need to talk about mental health without shame","trailText":"Juno Dawson, the transgender author formerly known as James, shares a very personal story about her anxiety attack at Hay festival for the very first time, and explains why she wrote her new teen advice guide Mind your Head","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>As a preface to the rest of this piece, I think it’s important to state that I travelled directly to the Hay Festival 2015 from the Eurovision Song Contest. After five <em>very</em> rainy days in Vienna I was, it’s fair to say, feeling a tiny bit hungover. This is an important fact, you shall see why shortly.<br /></p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/jan/16/james-dawson-this-book-is-gay-lgbt-mental-health-sex-education\">James Dawson: we need to take action on mental health of LGBT teens</a> </p> </aside>  <p> If you don’t know, the <a href=\"https://www.hayfestival.com/wales/index.aspx?skinid=2&amp;currencysetting=GBP&amp;localesetting=en-GB&amp;resetfilters=true\">Hay Festival</a> is one of the most prestigious literary festivals in the calendar. Last year, I joined a glittering array of children’s authors in being invited to speak. I was to appear on a special panel about the YA Book Prize with Louise O’Neill, Non Pratt and, my personal inspiration, Malorie Blackman.</p> <p> I drove my tired ass from the airport to Hay-On-Wye, the picturesque village where the festival takes place. Things didn’t get off to a <em>great</em> start when I parked the rental car against a plant pot at the hotel, scratching the bumper (an error I would later be fined £300 for). Nonetheless, I headed over to the festival site to meet up with Hot Key Books staff and the other authors for lunch.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2802c62f89339280309920b02586d809cf9b18e8\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/2802c62f89339280309920b02586d809cf9b18e8/0_378_2048_1229/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Juno Dawson at Hay festival\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Here’s Juno Dawson when she was known as James (second from right) with fellow teen authors Louise O’Neill, Malorie Blackman and Non Pratt at Hay festival, on the day of her anxiety attack.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p> I’ve been very lucky to do a lot of festivals and panel events. To be honest, they’ve never really phased me and I don’t get nervous. Before the event I was in good spirits, but then, about five minutes before we were due to go on stage, things took a very dark turn indeed.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/feb/08/mental-health-ya-fiction-teenagers-speak-out\">Mental health and books: teenagers speak out</a> </p> </aside>  <p> Before I divulge the horror of what happened next, allow me to explain Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS). Since I was a teenager, I’ve had IBS. Lots and lots of people do, we just don’t talk about it because we’re oh-so British and we don’t talk about bums, willies and ladygardens. The problem is that IBS – no one really knows what it is or why it happens – is at least partially psychosomatic, meaning it has a psychological element and physical consequences.</p> <p> For whatever reason, as we were being fitted with microphones, an IDEA entered my head: “you’re going to be sick,” an insidious little voice said.</p> <p>“I’m not,” I told myself, but immediately, my <em>head</em> started scanning my body for signs I might be ill. I <em>had</em> just eaten. I <em>did</em> feel quite full. Maybe I <em>would</em> be sick.</p> <p> From the first thought – <em>you’re going to be sick\u001F – </em>I entered a downward spiral that went something like this:</p> <p>You’re going to sick</p> <p>You’re going to be sick on stage</p> <p>You’re going to be sick and <em>Malorie Blackman</em> will see</p> <p>You’re going to be sick and Hay Festival will be horrified</p> <p><em>They’re all going to laugh at you, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrie_(1976_film)\">Carrie</a></em></p> <p>You’ll never be invited to another festival</p> <p>You’ll never get another book deal</p> <p>You’ll never write another book</p> <p>You’ll have to be a rent boy or worse, a teacher (I used to be a teacher)</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/feb/11/valentines-day-why-love-hurts-catherine-johnson\">Why love hurts – and it's always worth it</a> </p> </aside>  <p>By this stage we had been shepherded on stage (festivals run a very tight ship) and I fudged my way through a question about the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/love-hurts.html\">Love Hurts</a><em> </em>anthology (to this day I don’t remember what I actually said). My downward spiral was out of control, as you can see. None of it makes sense, I know, but when your heart is pounding and your head is spinning, it really feels like it could happen.<br /></p> <p> This is an anxiety or panic attack. The brain allows the release of a massive amount of the hormone adrenaline and your body is a slave it to. It triggers the “fight or flight” response, and on that occasion my body’s reaction was to feel like I was going to simultaneously vom and poop myself. Combine that with my life events – sleep deprivation, dehydration, a four hour drive, being a tiny bit transgender – and it was all too much.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2014/sep/04/this-book-is-gay-james-dawson\">Why my book is gay: and I'm proud of it</a> </p> </aside>  <p> When my heartbeat reached critical mass, I turned to Louise O Neill and whispered, “I have to get off this stage.” I legged it, much to everyone’s confusion, pulling off my little Britney head-mic as I went. One of the Hay volunteers helped me outside and showed me the way to the nearest toilet.</p> <p> I was not sick. It was all in my head.</p> <p> You see, as soon as I realised the world was not going to end – Malorie didn’t even stop mid-sentence as I fled – I was fine. The panel carried on just fine. I got some fresh air and said I was OK to go back onstage. I had a choice: I could say nothing, or tell the truth. So I told the truth. I went back and explained that sometimes I have anxiety attacks.</p> <p> The audience, the other panellists, the organisers of the festival were nothing but warm and supportive. The clap I got when I came back to the stage was a real turning point. I had nothing to hide and nothing to be ashamed of.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/aug/02/mental-health-relapse-holly-bourne-am-i-normal-yet\">Why we need to be honest about OCD and teen mental health</a> </p> </aside>  <p> That said, I wasn’t prepared to risk a career I’ve worked <em>very</em> hard on. I’m not going to let my mental health stop me. It’s funny; before the festival I had just completed my new book <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368025/\">Mind Your Head</a> but hadn’t been on SSRI medication (anti-anxiety drugs) before. This time, I decided enough was enough. I went to my GP and he agreed a course of mild anti-depressants would be the way forward, especially as we’d never tried them before. It took a couple of goes to get it right, but once we found the right drug, it made a huge difference.</p> <p> Now, when my head sends me a thought like “you’re going to be sick”, my brain <em>and</em> body responds with a “no, I’m not actually – you’re just an idea, do one.” As it is, after seven months on escitalopram, I came off the drug, this time with better coping strategies for when I felt an attack coming on.</p> <p> I wish I’d accepted that my IBS was a mental illness sooner. I wasted so much time thinking I had a stomach complaint. The reason I didn’t is because of the stigma around mental health. Basically, I didn’t want to be thought of as a broken, fragile, mad person. I don’t feel fragile and I don’t feel broken. In fact, once I was on the right drugs, I got better rapidly. You know, like I had any illness.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"aa716e3db83a12bff0bdebb2a5819fc6f69b26da\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/aa716e3db83a12bff0bdebb2a5819fc6f69b26da/0_0_2030_3118/651.jpg\" alt=\"Mind your Head by Juno Dawson\" width=\"651\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p> The driving force behind <strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368025/\">Mind Your Head</a></strong> was, not only to give advice and strategies for dealing with life, but to reduce the stigma around mental illness. I want us all to be able to speak about mental health without shame, without secrecy, so we can all get the help we need.</p> <p><strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368025/\">Mind Your Head</a> by Juno Dawson is available from the Guardian bookshop. </strong></p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fg4j","wordcount":"1152","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/7d3224ff9c5358bee608e2e19987cd26d3d7bfc3/0_262_4000_2403/140.jpg","standfirst":"<p>Juno Dawson, the transgender author formerly known as James, shares a very personal story about her anxiety attack at Hay festival for the very first time, and explains why she wrote her new teen advice guide <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368025/\">Mind your Head</a></p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/teen-mental-health-ibs-juno-dawson","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/08/teen-mental-health-ibs-juno-dawson","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"7d3224ff9c5358bee608e2e19987cd26d3d7bfc3","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/7d3224ff9c5358bee608e2e19987cd26d3d7bfc3/0_262_4000_2403/2000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/7d3224ff9c5358bee608e2e19987cd26d3d7bfc3","altText":"Juno Dawson","caption":"Juno Dawson: The driving force behind <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368025/\">Mind Your Head</a> was, not only to give advice and strategies for dealing with life, but to reduce the stigma around mental illness.","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"7d3224ff9c5358bee608e2e19987cd26d3d7bfc3","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/7d3224ff9c5358bee60