ow, chortle, and cachinnate again on Saturday night in Leeds when the Northern Section of the Old Boys’ Book Club recreates the adventures of the schoolboy characters invented by <a href=\"https://www.stellabooks.com/featured-book/billy-bunter-by-frank-richards\">Frank Richards</a>, who died on Christmas Eve.</p> <p>At this monthly meeting, however, members will hold a brief requiem for Richards before invoking the ghost of the Fat Owl.</p> <p>These men and women, whose average age is about 50, relive their childhoods by collecting <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jun/06/horror-fiction\">penny dreadfuls</a>, twopenny bloods, and, most of all, the school adventures written by Charles Hamilton under the name of Frank Richards and many other names. They have grieved deeply over his death.</p> <p><strong>Brought joy<br /></strong>In a letter of “heartfelt love” sent to the old man shortly before he died, the treasurer, Mr G. Allison, wrote: “In our opinion, you have brought more joy, pleasure, and happiness into this world of ours than any other person now living.”</p> <p>A large claim that. But for many collectors of boys’ books Greyfriars is so real that it is almost their second old school. One has only to look at their programmes to see how members have created a cult out of Bunter, the Famous Five, and their school friends.</p> <p>In one programme, described as “bumper” - and there is a word one does not normally find outside the blurbs of juvenilia - Mr G. Wilde composed a Greyfriars theme as it might have been written by Hoskins, the mad musician at the school who sometimes paid fags to listen to his works. They (the fags) stuffed their ears with cotton wool. The members listened entranced.</p> <p>Mr John Allison, brother of the treasurer, translated for members a Bunter story written in Latin by Frank Richards for the “Times Educational Supplement.”</p> <p><strong>Men in caps<br /></strong>At one meeting a group of grown men solemnly donned schoolboys’ caps to play parts in “Who Killed Gosling?” a play written by Mr G. Allison. Gosling, the Greyfriars porter, has been bribed with a flask of whisky by those cads and bounders, Vernon-Smith, Skinner, Snoop, and Stott, to let them break bounds. The insufferable, the ineffable Bunter substituted water for the whisky because they would not let him go with them. Gosling died from the shock - or rather appeared to do so, for all Greyfriars characters are too good to lose.</p> <p>Truly the funfulness is terrific at the meetings of the Northern Section of the Old Boys’ Book Club, as Hurree Jamset Ram Singh might say.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ftjb","wordcount":"421","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6b664024cb756900817d3e7ab295cf2ab42ef7a8/0_0_3516_2109/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-11T05:00:12Z","standfirst":"<p><strong>8 January 1962: </strong>Fans of the rotund schoolboy character pay homage to its creator, the late Frank Richards <br></p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/08/billy-bunter-comics-television-childrens","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/jan/08/billy-bunter-comics-television-childrens","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"6b664024cb756900817d3e7ab295cf2ab42ef7a8","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6b664024cb756900817d3e7ab295cf2ab42ef7a8/0_0_3516_2109/2000.jpg","typeData":{"picdarUrn":"PD*2457300","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6b664024cb756900817d3e7ab295cf2ab42ef7a8","altText":"Still from the children’s TV series Billy Bunter, starring Gerald Campion (centre).","caption":"Still from the children’s TV series Billy Bunter, starring Gerald Campion (centre).","source":"BBC archives","credit":"Photograph: BBC archives","mediaId":"6b664024cb756900817d3e7ab295cf2ab42ef7a8","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6b664024cb756900817d3e7ab295cf2ab42e